name.text: Domain and Range of a Function

questiontext.text:
Find the domain and range of \(f(x)={@fx@}\).

Give your answer as interval of the real numbers.

Note: To enter intervals of you real line, you should write the relevant text in the table below.

Intervals Input Syntax
\( [a,b] \) cc(a,b)
\( (a,b) \) oo(a,b)
\( [a,b) \) co(a,b)
\( (a,b] \) oc(a,b)
\( (a, \infty) \) oo(a,inf)
\( (-\infty, b] \) oc(-inf,b)
\( (-\infty, \infty) \) oo(-inf,inf)


(a) \(Dom(f)=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]

[[feedback:prt1]]

(b) \(Range(f) =\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]

[[feedback:prt2]]

generalfeedback.text:
Worked Solution

(a) To determine the domain of the function, we need to identify any restrictions on the values of \(x\) that would make the expression undefined.

Looking at the function expression \(f(x)={@fx@}\), we observe that there are no explicit limitations or restrictions on the variable \(x\).

Therefore, the domain of \(f(x)\) is all real numbers, which can be denoted as,

\( Dom(f) = \mathbb{R} = {@ta1@}\)


(b) Next, we determine the range of the function.
The range represents the set of all possible values that \(f(x)\) can attain as \(x\) varies.

Since we recognize that \(f(x)\) is a quadratic function, the range will be given by a half-line, \( [a, \infty) \) or \( (-\infty, a] \)
Where the maximum or minimum value of \(f(x)\) is determined by the vertex of the quadratic function.


To determine the vertex of the quadratic function, we can "complete the square".
Note: It is also possible to use a calculus method here to determine the turning point of the function, which is the same as the vertex.

{@simp:false;@}

\(\begin{align*} f(x) &= {@fx@} \\ &= {@line1@} \\ &= {@line2@} \end{align*}\)

{@simp:true;@}


Therefore, \(f(x)\) has a minimum value of {@yv@} since \(({@x - xv@})^2 \geq 0\)
Hence, the vertex of \(f(x)\) occurs at \( ({@xv@}, {@yv@}) \).

Then, considering the shape of a quadratic function, the range of the function \(f(x)\) can be expressed as:

\(Range(f)= \{ y \in \mathbb{R}: y \geq {@yv@} \} ={@ta2@}\).

prtincorrect.text: Incorrect answer.

falsefeedback.text:
The domian of \(f(x)\) is the set of value of \(x\) for which we can evaluate \(f(x)\).
In this case, there are no restrictions on the values for which \(f(x)\) can be evaluated and therefore,

\( Range(f) = \mathbb{R} = {@ta1@}\)

\(f(x)\) is a quadratic function and so has the shape of a parabola.

The minimum value of the function can be determined by finding the turning point or "vertex" of the parabola, either by completing the square, differentiating or by using a known formula for the vertex.

The range of the function is the set of potential \(y\)-coordinates of points on this graph. Therefore, once we have found the minimum value, \(a\) we can see that the range of \(f\) is given by \( [a, \infty) \).
